1
00:00:02,570 --> 00:00:05,200
Over the last 60 years
4400 people have been abducted.

2
00:00:08,250 --> 00:00:10,140
All at once they were returned.

3
00:00:17,190 --> 00:00:19,140
With no memory of
where they've been.

4
00:00:21,030 --> 00:00:22,730
They haven't aged a day.

5
00:00:26,520 --> 00:00:28,310
And some have returned
with new abilities.

6
00:00:31,720 --> 00:00:33,690
all are trying to reconnect...

7
00:00:36,530 --> 00:00:38,170
...with a life interrupted.

8
00:00:38,200 --> 00:00:40,600
We're not a threat,
we're salvation.

9
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:42,900
The world
will have to deal with us.

10
00:00:44,800 --> 00:00:46,900
Previously on the 4400...

11
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:48,300
you're so sweet.

12
00:00:48,300 --> 00:00:51,600
I wish i could take you with me when i go, but i can't.

13
00:00:51,600 --> 00:00:54,470
Yesterday, a few patients were compelled to work on this thing,

14
00:00:54,471 --> 00:00:56,500
and today,
it's the entire hospital.

15
00:00:56,500 --> 00:00:58,170
If we get tess
out of here,

16
00:00:58,180 --> 00:00:59,850
do you think
this compulsion will fade?

17
00:00:59,851 --> 00:01:04,400
I'm injecting myself with a modified version of the promicin serum.

18
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:08,100
I will have taught my body how to produce promicin,

19
00:01:08,100 --> 00:01:13,550
and then i will be the first non-returnee
to develop 4400 abilities.

20
00:01:31,500 --> 00:01:33,500
Enough running, dr. Burkhoff.

21
00:01:33,500 --> 00:01:34,800
You need to come with us now.

22
00:01:34,800 --> 00:01:35,700
No.

23
00:01:35,700 --> 00:01:36,700
Stay back.

24
00:01:36,700 --> 00:01:37,500
I don't want to
hurt anyone.

25
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:39,100
That's very reassuring.

26
00:01:40,440 --> 00:01:42,000
We'll keep that in mind.

27
00:01:42,200 --> 00:01:43,700
No! No!

28
00:01:44,700 --> 00:01:45,200
 No!

29
00:02:29,300 --> 00:02:31,145
Mr. Tyler. Come in.

30
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:32,730
What can i do
for you?

31
00:02:34,100 --> 00:02:36,500
I wanted to ask you about your work
with the students here.

32
00:02:37,500 --> 00:02:38,300
Sure.

33
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:40,400
I teach three classes,
history, art, and...

34
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:42,200
i'm not talking
about your teaching.

35
00:02:43,400 --> 00:02:45,100
I was talking about the "counseling" that you do.

36
00:02:45,100 --> 00:02:47,600
I understand you use your ability
with the kids?

37
00:02:47,600 --> 00:02:49,600
That's right.

38
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:53,000
My ability is to help them
focus their abilities.

39
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:54,200
It's pretty much
what i've been doing

40
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:55,800
ever since i came back.

41
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:57,800
If a student
has a talent...

42
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:00,100
like all of our kids here do...

43
00:03:00,100 --> 00:03:01,500
i help them learn
how to use it,

44
00:03:01,500 --> 00:03:03,000
gain control of it,
build their confidence.

45
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:04,900
Does it work with adults?

46
00:03:04,900 --> 00:03:06,000
It didn't used to,

47
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,580
but i haven't tried it since i've been
off the inhibitor.

48
00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:09,700
 Why?

49
00:03:21,200 --> 00:03:24,500
I developed this ability
a few months ago...

50
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:27,400
telekinesis.

51
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:30,500
What a word, huh?

52
00:03:30,500 --> 00:03:31,700
I can't even say it
with a straight face.

53
00:03:31,700 --> 00:03:33,200
That's fantastic.

54
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:34,800
I've just been pretending
it isn't there.

55
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:37,900
I mean, i know
a little bit about it.

56
00:03:37,900 --> 00:03:39,800
So far, it only works
with inanimate objects,

57
00:03:39,800 --> 00:03:41,400
little stuff.

58
00:03:42,800 --> 00:03:45,400
But when i'm mad or excited,

59
00:03:45,400 --> 00:03:47,900
i can do a lot more
with it.

60
00:03:47,900 --> 00:03:49,800
And you're looking to control it
when you're calm?

61
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:53,300
Yeah, that's why i'm here,
i guess.

62
00:03:53,300 --> 00:03:58,000
How many times do i have to go over this
with you people?

63
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:03,000
I have not been injecting promicininto anyone but myself.

64
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:04,300
You're certain of that?

65
00:04:04,300 --> 00:04:06,900
You're a world-class
scientist.

66
00:04:06,900 --> 00:04:08,200
I find it
difficult to believe

67
00:04:08,200 --> 00:04:10,800
you wouldn't build a redundancy plan 
into your experiment.

68
00:04:10,800 --> 00:04:13,300
This isn't
your basic sleep study.

69
00:04:13,300 --> 00:04:15,500
I mean, look at me.

70
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:19,900
Do you think
i'd have an easy time finding volunteers?

71
00:04:21,500 --> 00:04:23,300
No. I do not.

72
00:04:23,300 --> 00:04:24,700
Oh.

73
00:04:32,700 --> 00:04:35,300
You look like you're in
quite a bit of discomfort to me.

74
00:04:35,300 --> 00:04:38,500
Yes.

75
00:04:40,900 --> 00:04:42,300
Well...

76
00:04:42,300 --> 00:04:43,600
you can relax now.

77
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:45,400
The experiment's over.

78
00:04:47,200 --> 00:04:48,400
This will only hurt
for a minute.

79
00:04:55,730 --> 00:04:57,600
Bag him.

80
00:04:57,600 --> 00:04:59,400
We'll take him back
for the autopsy.

81
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:15,000
Get dr. Burkhoff
up there quickly.

82
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:18,000
They promised results
by the morning.

83
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:43,100
Mommy?

84
00:06:44,200 --> 00:06:46,000
Mommy?

85
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,100
Are you okay?

86
00:06:48,100 --> 00:06:51,500
Oh, of course, sweetie.
I'm fine.

87
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:53,400
Why wouldn't i be?

88
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:56,800
I had a bad dream,
and you were in it.

89
00:06:56,800 --> 00:07:00,500
Well, you get in
and tell me about it.

90
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:07,500
You turned into
a monster.

91
00:07:07,500 --> 00:07:10,300
It was horrible.

92
00:07:10,300 --> 00:07:12,800
It seemed so real.

93
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:14,100
It was you.

94
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:17,400
But you
were different.

95
00:07:20,200 --> 00:07:22,800
What kind
of a monster?

96
00:07:22,800 --> 00:07:24,200
Nice.

97
00:07:24,200 --> 00:07:25,800
Something
for the refrigerator door.

98
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,300
You don't think there's anything
to this?

99
00:07:28,300 --> 00:07:29,500
It's not a prediction,
right?

100
00:07:29,500 --> 00:07:30,600
Just a bad dream.

101
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:32,100
Well, i hope so, but when your daughter's
a precog,

102
00:07:32,101 --> 00:07:34,300
you don't want her
giving you a picture like this.

103
00:07:36,258 --> 00:07:37,600
Hello.
This is skouris.

104
00:07:39,150 --> 00:07:40,392
Well, thank you
for calling me back.

105
00:07:40,392 --> 00:07:42,000
Let me know if you see him, all right?

106
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:43,700
Everything okay?

107
00:07:44,280 --> 00:07:45,358
Maybe.

108
00:07:46,100 --> 00:07:46,720
I'm not sure.

109
00:07:47,200 --> 00:07:49,000
I mean, that was
the 4400 center.

110
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,300
I was hoping maybe
they'd seen dr. Burkhoff.

111
00:07:51,300 --> 00:07:53,100
I stopped by
his apartment yesterday,

112
00:07:53,100 --> 00:07:54,000
and he wasn't home.

113
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:55,900
Uh, diana.

114
00:07:55,900 --> 00:07:58,600
Why would you be stopping by
dr. Burkhoff's apartment?

115
00:07:59,600 --> 00:08:02,000
You actually saw the wound in kevin's hand
heal over?

116
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:03,100
Yes.

117
00:08:03,100 --> 00:08:04,700
He pulled the scalpel out, and it was gone
within seconds.

118
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:07,900
He's developing
an ability.

119
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:10,100
I mean, he's close
to it, anyway.

120
00:08:10,100 --> 00:08:12,200
He said
it comes and goes.

121
00:08:13,640 --> 00:08:14,300
What?

122
00:08:14,300 --> 00:08:17,600
Anyone else developing
a 4400 ability i should know about?

123
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:19,400
I should have
told you earlier.

124
00:08:19,400 --> 00:08:20,800
You're damn right
you should have.

125
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,000
Got to hand it
to you, diana...

126
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:23,711
some people play racketball,
in their spare time,

127
00:08:24,020 --> 00:08:25,142
maybe collect old records.
But you?

128
00:08:25,143 --> 00:08:27,600
You play igor
to the one man who...

129
00:08:29,600 --> 00:08:31,500
Well, if he has developed
an ability, like you say,

130
00:08:32,900 --> 00:08:34,600
maybe he really is
the father of 4400 technology,

131
00:08:34,600 --> 00:08:36,700
just like the future predicted.

132
00:08:38,300 --> 00:08:40,200
Are you two the only ones
who know about this experiment?

133
00:08:41,318 --> 00:08:42,400
I thought we were...

134
00:08:42,400 --> 00:08:45,103
and now i'm not so sure,

135
00:08:45,800 --> 00:08:46,400
and that's what
i'm worried about.

136
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:50,000
Tom, what if someone else finds out 
what he's up to?

137
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:51,500
Well, if he succeeds,
we could be talking

138
00:08:51,500 --> 00:08:53,900
about the mass-marketing
of 4400 abilities.

139
00:08:54,240 --> 00:08:56,500
I'm sure a lot of people would
like to keep that genie in the bottle.

140
00:08:57,695 --> 00:08:58,800
Wouldn't make our jobs
any easier.

141
00:08:57,900 --> 00:09:00,100
Are you...
are you okay?

142
00:09:00,100 --> 00:09:02,800
That's just my allergies
are acting up.

143
00:09:02,819 --> 00:09:04,749
I've already spoken
to his family.

144
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:06,067
They haven't heard from him
in months.

145
00:09:06,067 --> 00:09:08,100
Okay, so who else
is he close to?

146
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:13,100
I didn't know that cheshire cats
always grinned...

147
00:09:13,100 --> 00:09:18,400
In fact, i didn't know that cats could grin, said alice
very politely.

148
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:21,169
"You don't know much,"
said the duchess.

149
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:22,992
"And that's a fact."

150
00:09:25,400 --> 00:09:28,800
We'll finish this chapter
tomorrow.

151
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:31,200
I hope you all can make it.

152
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:34,900
I've been living in a halfway house
for about three months.

153
00:09:34,900 --> 00:09:37,500
I got this job here
two weeks ago.

154
00:09:37,500 --> 00:09:37,920
That's great, tess.

155
00:09:37,927 --> 00:09:40,900
So they found a medication
that works for you?

156
00:09:40,900 --> 00:09:43,000
So far, so good.

157
00:09:43,626 --> 00:09:45,317
I still
have my disease.

158
00:09:45,400 --> 00:09:47,800
Schizophrenia
never goes away,

159
00:09:47,800 --> 00:09:51,400
but i haven't had
any symptoms for a while.

160
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:53,300
Hopefully i won't.

161
00:09:53,300 --> 00:09:56,800
So these kids you're reading to,
they're not going to try and build a tower

162
00:09:56,800 --> 00:09:59,400
To contact the future,
are they?

163
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:02,600
I don't think so.

164
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:05,060
I can barely remember
all that now.

165
00:10:05,678 --> 00:10:08,600
I'm still not sure how i could compel people
to work,

166
00:10:08,600 --> 00:10:13,000
or why they put those blueprints
in my head.

167
00:10:14,220 --> 00:10:15,200
I'm glad
it made kevin better,

168
00:10:15,200 --> 00:10:18,100
but it was still so weird.

169
00:10:18,100 --> 00:10:20,600
That's actually
why we're here.

170
00:10:20,600 --> 00:10:22,400
Have you been in touch
with kevin lately?

171
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:23,800
No.

172
00:10:23,800 --> 00:10:27,900
I called him when i first got out
of the institution

173
00:10:27,900 --> 00:10:29,700
We met for coffee,

174
00:10:29,700 --> 00:10:31,800
but i haven't seen him
in months.

175
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,200
Is he okay?

176
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:34,600
Well,
we're not sure,

177
00:10:34,600 --> 00:10:35,700
but we'd like to
talk to him.

178
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:38,000
So, if he contacts you,
would you let us know?

179
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:39,300
Well, of course.

180
00:10:39,300 --> 00:10:42,300
When you find him,
will you have him call me?

181
00:10:42,300 --> 00:10:43,500
Sure.

182
00:10:43,500 --> 00:10:45,051
It's nice to see you
again, tess.

183
00:10:46,280 --> 00:10:47,264
Bye.

184
00:10:51,285 --> 00:10:52,800
I just spoke
with the program coordinator.

185
00:10:52,800 --> 00:10:56,239
She says the first segment will be interviews
with some of the people you've healed

186
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:57,900
and then they'll bring you out after the break.

187
00:10:57,900 --> 00:10:59,300
She says the emotional stuff also plays well
with her audience,

188
00:10:59,300 --> 00:11:01,000
also plays well
with her audience,

189
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:05,600
- So feel free to cry or...
- We'll see about that.

190
00:11:05,600 --> 00:11:07,689
They're also curious
about the wedding.

191
00:11:07,690 --> 00:11:09,500
She'd love it if you answered
some questions...

192
00:11:09,500 --> 00:11:11,800
let's keep the private life
private, okay?

193
00:11:11,800 --> 00:11:12,900
Nick!

194
00:11:12,900 --> 00:11:14,500
Nick, please,
wake up!

195
00:11:14,700 --> 00:11:15,700
Nick!

196
00:11:15,700 --> 00:11:18,600
Nick, please,
wake up!

197
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:23,066
Oh, jesus,
that's nick crowley.

198
00:11:23,067 --> 00:11:24,000
Oh, my god.

199
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:26,645
You're that 4400,
the one with the hands.

200
00:11:26,800 --> 00:11:28,000
Help him, please!
Nick!

201
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:31,000
Nick, wake up. Please!

202
00:11:47,500 --> 00:11:49,900
If you're okay,
say something.

203
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:54,235
Well, jim morrison says hello.

204
00:11:58,500 --> 00:12:01,300
Easy. Easy, boys, easy.

205
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:05,400
You just saved nick crowley.

206
00:12:06,400 --> 00:12:09,200
On behalf of millions of rock and roll
burnouts all over the world,

207
00:12:09,500 --> 00:12:11,400
Allow me to thank you.

208
00:12:13,600 --> 00:12:16,593
Any time you want to lay these on me,
you just let me know.

209
00:12:17,800 --> 00:12:19,600
It was a little bit big,

210
00:12:19,600 --> 00:12:21,200
so i just had it resized.

211
00:12:21,200 --> 00:12:24,400
It's perfect now.

212
00:12:26,700 --> 00:12:30,600
I think, mom would be really happy,
don't you?

213
00:12:30,600 --> 00:12:32,800
Lily gave you
that ring.

214
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:35,700
I guess you can do
what you want with it.

215
00:12:37,600 --> 00:12:40,100
I think it's perfect.

216
00:12:41,900 --> 00:12:44,660
Have you thought about what you're going to say
at the wedding?

217
00:12:45,300 --> 00:12:47,260
Usually, the father of the bride gives a toast.

218
00:12:48,100 --> 00:12:49,800
Um...

219
00:12:49,800 --> 00:12:51,700
Well.

220
00:12:51,700 --> 00:12:53,800
It's all been so sudden.

221
00:12:53,800 --> 00:12:56,100
I haven't had much time
to really plan it yet.

222
00:12:56,101 --> 00:12:56,770
That's okay.

223
00:12:56,800 --> 00:12:58,440
I have a few thoughts.

224
00:13:00,143 --> 00:13:02,862
There's an article
in this magazine on toasts.

225
00:13:05,602 --> 00:13:06,740
Read it.

226
00:13:08,400 --> 00:13:10,480
I think i can handle that
on my own.

227
00:13:10,481 --> 00:13:11,867
Dad, i want you to read it.

228
00:13:12,800 --> 00:13:13,900
Tonight.

229
00:13:33,500 --> 00:13:34,905
Hi.

230
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:40,300
I bought some food.

231
00:13:41,300 --> 00:13:43,222
Let me help you with that.

232
00:13:43,600 --> 00:13:44,763
Thank you.

233
00:13:45,400 --> 00:13:48,400
My joints
are a little stiff.

234
00:13:49,900 --> 00:13:53,308
Kevin, why did you put your hood up
when i came in?

235
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:58,930
You shouldn't have to
look at me like this.

236
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:06,856
Like what?

237
00:14:13,700 --> 00:14:17,129
Diana skouris and tom baldwin
came by the bookstore today.

238
00:14:17,600 --> 00:14:19,116
They were asking
about you.

239
00:14:19,700 --> 00:14:21,444
I figured
diana would be worried.

240
00:14:21,445 --> 00:14:22,551
How did she look?

241
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:25,808
Okay, i guess.

242
00:14:26,400 --> 00:14:27,959
A little sick.

243
00:14:29,500 --> 00:14:31,513
Kevin, i felt bad
seeing her.

244
00:14:31,514 --> 00:14:34,350
I don't like what we're doing to her...
what i'm doing to her...

245
00:14:34,351 --> 00:14:41,587
I don't like it much either, but we are on the cusp
of changing the world...

246
00:14:41,700 --> 00:14:42,600
For the better.

247
00:14:43,500 --> 00:14:45,800
We have to keep going,
even if it gets ugly.

248
00:14:45,800 --> 00:14:47,400
Kevin, it's already ugly.

249
00:14:47,400 --> 00:14:49,000
Someone shot you yesterday.

250
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:55,103
I know, but the experiment is worth the risk.

251
00:14:55,400 --> 00:14:57,356
They woke me up
to do this.

252
00:14:57,500 --> 00:15:00,622
You woke me up
to do this.

253
00:15:00,623 --> 00:15:04,092
I have to move forward.

254
00:15:04,900 --> 00:15:07,800
And to do that,
i need diana.

255
00:15:12,612 --> 00:15:13,888
And i need you.

256
00:15:33,100 --> 00:15:35,000
Is shawn farrell around?

257
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:36,400
I have something for him.

258
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:40,500
Oh!

259
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:42,638
I played that when we were recording
my first album.

260
00:15:43,900 --> 00:15:45,200
I've been holding onto it
for years.

